            "text": "## Compact, auditable reasoning trace\n\n**Confirmed facts**\n- At 08:20 IST, 14 medication reminders were delivered approximately 60 minutes late.\n- Delivery timing returned to normal at 08:47 IST.\n- A daylight-saving-time configuration change occurred.\n- No missed doses have been confirmed.\n- One user reported taking medication later than usual; causation is unestablished.\n- The next stakeholder update is scheduled for 10:00 IST.\n- Procedure requires immediate notification to the clinical safety lead when medication timing could plausibly be affected.\n\n**Hypotheses / unknowns**\n- The configuration change is a suspected, not confirmed, cause.\n- The full scope of affected users and any clinical impact are unknown.\n- Whether the user’s delayed medication was caused by the incident is unknown.\n\n**Communication risks**\n- Presenting the suspected cause as confirmed.\n- Implying no patient impact based only on no confirmed missed doses.\n- Claiming resolution beyond the observed return to normal timing.\n- Omitting required clinical-safety escalation.\n\n**Decisions both outputs must reflect**\n- State observed facts and uncertainty precisely.\n- Report current timing as normal without claiming a confirmed root cause or customer outcome.\n- Include immediate clinical safety lead notification.\n- Provide the next update at 10:00 IST.\n\n## 1. Customer/stakeholder update\n\nAt 08:20 IST, 14 medication reminders were delivered approximately 60 minutes late following a daylight-saving-time configuration change. Delivery timing returned to normal at 08:47 IST, and we are continuing to investigate. No missed doses have been confirmed. One user reported taking medication later than usual, but we have not established that this was caused by the incident. The configuration change is currently a suspected cause, not a confirmed root cause. In accordance with our healthcare safety procedure, the clinical safety lead is being notified. We will provide the next stakeholder update at 10:00 IST.\n\n## 2. Internal engineering action recommendation\n\n- Notify the clinical safety lead immediately, as required by procedure.\n- Preserve and review configuration-change, scheduling, and delivery logs covering the affected period.\n- Determine the affected population and verify whether any other reminders were delayed.\n- Test the daylight-saving-time configuration and scheduling behavior; do not treat it as the confirmed root cause until validated.\n- Prepare the 10:00 IST update with verified scope, findings, and any confirmed safety impact."
